Java has a [String.format][1] method that works similarly to this.  [Here&#39;s an example of how to use it.][2]  This is the [documentation reference][3] that explains what all those `%` options can be.

And here&#39;s an inlined example:

    package com.sandbox;

    public class Sandbox {
    
        public static void main(String[] args) {
            System.out.println(String.format(&quot;It is %d oclock&quot;, 5));
        }        
    }

This prints &quot;It is 5 oclock&quot;.

  [1]: http://docs.oracle.com/javase/6/docs/api/java/lang/String.html#format%28java.lang.String,%20java.lang.Object...%29
  [2]: https://stackoverflow.com/a/3695253/61624
  [3]: http://docs.oracle.com/javase/1.5.0/docs/api/java/util/Formatter.html#syntax

You can do this (using [String.format)][1]:

    int x = 4;
    int y = 5;
        
    String res = String.format(&quot;%d + %d = %d&quot;, x, y, x+y);
    System.out.println(res); // prints &quot;4 + 5 = 9&quot;

    res = String.format(&quot;%d %d&quot;, x, y);
    System.out.println(res); // prints &quot;4 5&quot;


  [1]: http://docs.oracle.com/javase/1.5.0/docs/api/java/lang/String.html#format%28java.lang.String,%20java.lang.Object...%29

The [`MessageFormat`][1] class looks like what you&#39;re after.

    System.out.println(MessageFormat.format(&quot;{0} + {1} = {2}&quot;, x, y, x + y));

[1]: http://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/text/MessageFormat.html

If you want to use empty placeholders (without positions), you could write a small utility around `Message.format()`, like this

    
        void print(String s, Object... var2) {
            int i = 0;
            while(s.contains(&quot;{}&quot;)) {
                s = s.replaceFirst(Pattern.quote(&quot;{}&quot;), &quot;{&quot;+ i++ +&quot;}&quot;);
            }
            System.out.println(MessageFormat.format(s, var2));
        }


And then, can use it like,

    print(&quot;{} + {} = {}&quot;, 4, 5, 4 + 5);

